&gt;  &gt; and decide how best to provide feedback, and fix the most important
&gt;  &gt; bugs.
&gt;  &gt;
&gt;  &gt; /steve@... &lt;mailto:%2Fsteve%40archive.org&gt;
&gt;  &gt;
&gt;  &gt;
&gt;  &gt; On 4/16/10 12:58 PM, Nat Ayewah wrote:
&gt;  &gt; &gt; Hi Steve,
&gt;  &gt; &gt;
&gt;  &gt; &gt; Thanks for taking a look at this. One of our goals is to keep the cloud
&gt;  &gt; &gt; updated with the state of the project (e.g. by analyzing the nightly
&gt;  &gt; &gt; build). This is especially useful if you mark a warning as &quot;Not-A-Bug&quot;,
&gt;  &gt; &gt; so it can be suppressed, and this information is remembered.
&gt;  &gt; &gt;
&gt;  &gt; &gt; Perhaps the best short-term solution would be for you to point me to
&gt;  &gt; the
&gt;  &gt; &gt; build-artifacts produced after each nightly build. I can set up the
&gt;  &gt; &gt; cloud to download, analyze, and update the cloud after each build.
&gt;  &gt; &gt; Eventually can have the continuous build update the cloud directly.
&gt;  &gt; &gt;
&gt;  &gt; &gt; I have more specific answers to some of your queries below:
&gt;  &gt; &gt;
&gt;  &gt; &gt;&gt; we&#39;ll need to learn
&gt;  &gt; &gt;&gt; how to tell FindBugs how to find &quot;missing classes needed for
&gt;  &gt; &gt;&gt; analysis&quot;, and how to exclude &quot;bugs&quot; which we want ignored.
&gt;  &gt; &gt;&gt;
&gt;  &gt; &gt; I ran the analysis on H3. My approach was to download
&gt;  &gt; &gt; heritrix-3.0.0-dist.tar.gz, bundle all the jars, and separate out the
&gt;  &gt; &gt; ones that contain analysis classes and auxillary classes. From the
&gt;  &gt; &gt; command line, I use the following commands (assumes FindBugs is on the
&gt;  &gt; &gt; path):
&gt;  &gt; &gt;
&gt;  &gt; &gt; find heritrix-3.0.0 -name &quot;*.jar&quot; &gt; analysis.txt
&gt;  &gt; &gt; rejarForAnalysis -inputFileList analysis.txt -auxFileList analysis.txt
&gt;  &gt; &gt; -prefix org.archive
&gt;  &gt; &gt;
&gt;  &gt; &gt; This creates two jars &#39;analyze.jar&#39; and &#39;auxilary.jar&#39; that I use as my
&gt;  &gt; &gt; analysis target and auxilary class path respectively. There may be some
&gt;  &gt; &gt; classes missing -- FindBugs does a &quot;best-effort&quot; analysis and the
&gt;  &gt; &gt; missing classes don&#39;t necessarily lead to lots of missing warnings.
&gt;  &gt; &gt;
&gt;  &gt; &gt; To exclude entire bug patterns, I would use a FindBugs filter file
&gt;  &gt; &gt; described at: http://findbugs.sourceforge.net/manual/filter.html
&gt; &lt;http://findbugs.sourceforge.net/manual/filter.html&gt;
&gt;  &gt; &gt;
&gt;  &gt; &gt;&gt;
&gt;  &gt; &gt;&gt; i really like the FindBugs Eclipse plugin, but don&#39;t see a way
&gt;  &gt; &gt;&gt; to get &quot;-emacs&quot;-like output from it, and it doesn&#39;t look like
&gt;  &gt; &gt;&gt; annotations (in the Bug User Annotations view) can be uploaded
&gt;  &gt; &gt;&gt; to the cloud from the plugin.
&gt;  &gt; &gt;&gt;
&gt;  &gt; &gt; The Eclipse plugin is currently being updated to support the new cloud
&gt;  &gt; &gt; features.
&gt;  &gt; &gt;&gt;
&gt;  &gt; &gt;&gt;
&gt;  &gt; &gt;&gt; when i open the Web Start client, it says &quot;not signed in&quot;, but
&gt;  &gt; &gt;&gt; the Comunity Review page says a seperate browser window will
&gt;  &gt; &gt;&gt; open to login with OpenId. is there another way to login to the
&gt;  &gt; &gt;&gt; review?
&gt;  &gt; &gt;&gt;
&gt;  &gt; &gt; We recently changed the workflow so you do not need to sign in unless
&gt;  &gt; &gt; you want to review a warning. When you try to do this, a message
&gt;  &gt; &gt; prompting you to sign in comes up. I&#39;ve updated the Community Review
&gt;  &gt; &gt; page &lt;http://findbugs.cs.umd.edu/cloud/
&gt; &lt;http://findbugs.cs.umd.edu/cloud/&gt;&gt; to reflect this.
&gt;  &gt; &gt;&gt;
&gt;  &gt; &gt;&gt;
&gt;  &gt; &gt;&gt; which version of Heritrix was analyzed to produce the bugs in
&gt;  &gt; &gt;&gt; the FindBugs Cloud? is there a way to see the options that were
&gt;  &gt; &gt;&gt; used to produce the cloud report for a particular project?
&gt;  &gt; &gt;&gt;
&gt;  &gt; &gt; I analyzed heritrix-3.0.0. The warnings were filtered to only include
&gt;  &gt; &gt; warnings with bug ranks 1-14 and with associated source files. The
&gt;  &gt; exact
&gt;  &gt; &gt; commands were:
&gt;  &gt; &gt;
&gt;  &gt; &gt; findbugs -textui -xml *-output db.xml* -auxclasspath auxilary.jar
&gt;  &gt; &gt; analyze.jar
&gt;  &gt; &gt; setBugDatabaseInfo -resetProject -purgeStats -findSource [srcdir]
&gt;  &gt; &gt; *db.xml updated-db.xml*
&gt;  &gt; &gt; filterBugs -withSource -maxRank 14 -priority M -dontUpdateStats
&gt;  &gt; &gt; *updated-db.xml updated-db.xml*
&gt;  &gt; &gt;
&gt;  &gt; &gt;&gt; it would be nice to reconcile the cloud bugs with the bugs i
&gt;  &gt; &gt;&gt; find with a local client, so we can track them together.
&gt;  &gt; &gt;&gt; otherwise, i&#39;ll need to open a seperate issue simply to provide
&gt;  &gt; &gt;&gt; feedback to the cloud for Community Review. do you have another
&gt;  &gt; &gt;&gt; recommendation?
&gt;  &gt; &gt;&gt;
&gt;  &gt; &gt; We recently added features to FindBugs HEAD
&gt;  &gt; &gt;
&gt; &lt;http://code.google.com/p/findbugs/source/browse/#svn/trunk/findbugs
&gt; &lt;http://code.google.com/p/findbugs/source/browse/#svn/trunk/findbugs&gt;&gt;
&gt;  &gt; &gt; that allow you to connect your local analysis to the cloud. This is
&gt;  &gt; &gt; still under development, but I can show you this if you are interested.
&gt;  &gt; &gt;
&gt;  &gt; &gt; Thanks,
&gt;  &gt; &gt; Nat
